{{otherpeople|George Hill}} {{Infobox figure skater |name= George Hill |image= |caption= |country= [[United States]] |fullname= George Edward Bellows Hill |birth_date= {{Birth date|1907|4|24}} |birth_place= [[Boston, Massachusetts]] |death_date= {{death date and age|1992|5|4|1907|4|24}} |death_place= [[Kentfield, California]] |partner= [[Maribel Vinson]] |formercoach= |formerchoreographer= |skating club= [[SC of Boston]] |retired= |medaltemplates = <!-- see [[Template:MedalRelatedTemplates]] --> {{MedalCountry | [[United States]]}} {{MedalSport|Ladies' [[figure skating]]}} {{MedalSport|Pairs [[figure skating]]}} {{MedalCompetition|[[North American Figure Skating Championships|North American Championships]]}} {{MedalSilver|[[1937 North American Figure Skating Championships|1937 Boston]]|Pairs}} {{MedalGold|[[1935 North American Figure Skating Championships|1935 Montreal]]|Pairs}} }} '''George Edward Bellows Hill''' (April 24, 1907 in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] &ndash; May 7, 1992 in [[Kentfield, California]]) was an [[United States|American]] [[figure skater]] who competed in [[single skating]] and [[pair skating]]. As a pair skater, he was the 1933, 1935, 1936, and 1937 [[United States Figure Skating Championships|U.S. national champion]] with partner [[Maribel Vinson]]. As a single skater, he was the 1930, 1931, 1934, and 1936 U.S. bronze medalist.
He competed in singles at the [[1931 World Figure Skating Championships]], where he placed 11th.<ref>[http://www.eskatefans.com/skatabase/worldmen1930.html Skatabase: 1930s Worlds Men's Singles Results]</ref> He represented the [[United States at the 1936 Winter Olympics]] in both singles and pairs. He placed 22nd in singles and 5th in pairs with Vinson.<ref>{{PDF|[http://www.usfigureskating.org/content/events/200506/olympics/olympic-medalists.pdf Historical Placements: US Olympic Figure Skating Team]|260&nbsp;[[Kibibyte|KiB]]<!-- application/pdf, 266328 bytes -->}}</ref>
